Recently my upside down show gel cap was rot away and I decided to print a new one. The original cap was cheap material and had no silicone valve. My first tries to just print a new cap with a thin bottom and just cut a cross inside the bottom were failed. The gel was dripping endless. So, here is my approach for a threaded upside down show gel cap with a valve from any upside down kitchen bottle, i.e. honey bottle, sirup bottle, BBQ sauce bottle ... I used the latter one and cutted this out of the empty bottle. Instructions:

  • Cut out the valve from any upside down plastic bottle to fit in part 1.

  • Adjust inner diameter or thread winding in OpenSCAD (or leave it at 27 mm). Then print the 2 parts.

  • Knead a chewing gum or other sealing material into a ring slightly bigger than the open hole and put it in the inside of part 1.

  • Press the new valve through the ring from the inside of part 1. If it does not fit well, use a hair dryer to weaken and widen the hole.

  • Knead another small sealant ring and put it around the valve.

  • Press part 2 onto the valve. Again, if it does not fit in part 1, use a hair dryer to weaken it.
    • The hair dryer also helps you screwing the cap onto the shower bottle for the first time.

The included script threads.scad is from Dan Kirshner - [email protected] with the following quote:

A simple sketchup for making custom combs for electrophoresis such as PCR.
If you download the script and open it with OpenSCAD, the third to last line is commented out for the ability to export 2d projections of the design (dxf).
This is useful if you wish to laser cut out the combs. Since most combs need to be thin, it is recommended to laser cut out or CNC engineered plastic (acetal delrin or polycarbonate are two good choices).
Default spacing in this script includes standard 8 channel pipetter and 1/2 8 channel for loading every other well.
Our eletrophoresis chambers support 21 teeth with 8-channel spacing. Once cut out, you just mount these combs to a rigid spine (to flatten them out) and drop them down to the bottom of the gel. This can be done with anything from binder clips to screw mounts. The two side "wells" are to keep the remaining ones a constant depth. First set of testing results:
As long as the spine holds the material flat, it works very well even down at 0.5mm gap between teeth. Loading the wells can be difficult at the current dimensions of the well (because it is roughly the width of a pipette tip). 3x and 2x 8-channel spacing were tested at 1, 0.75, and 0.5mm gap between teeth (1% gel).
Well depth spacer from the bottom should be reduced to 1mm (defaults to 2mm) to require less gel.

Cutting Settings My lab selected 0.04" delrin plastic to cut out these combs (http://www.mcmaster.com/#8738k26/=10ttjiw).
I cut these out on an 30W epilog CO2 laser. Since the sheet came rolled up, I used a cardboard cover to ensure the material stayed flat for the cut. I cut out a rectangle from the cardboard as a window for the plastic. Settings were 25% speed, 80% power, single pass.
Job was cut out in a bit under 2 minutes (with default settings). It was a bit over 2 minutes with more teeth on the second side.

This is a simple, adjustable z-stop bracket for a Reprap i2 or any 3d printer that needs to hold a stopper switch. Its made to mount to an 8mm rod in the standard position that Reprap i2 usually mounts its z-stop. The parts are as follows:
  • zstop.stl - the "main mounting bracket" for mounting to the printer.
  • zstop-part2.stl - is the "stop switch bracket" that gets attached to the z-stop switch, and then attached to the "main mounting bracket" in #1 above.
  • zstop-part2-right.stl - identical part to #2, but the screw positions are reversed. if your not sure, this is probably the correct one to print.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

i2

Supports:

No

Resolution:

3.5mm

Infill:

70%

Notes: The tolerances are tight. Its made so you sand the moving parts to get them smooth. its important not to have any play in the part movements.

Assembly and Important note: The main mounting bracket will interfere with your X-end-motor as it descends because it may not hit the z-stop switch before interfering with the bracket. Watch the video. I glued a small "button like" slider (basically a rigid plastic disk) underneat the X-end-motor so it hits the switch well before these two parts collide. Its a simple thing to make but i did not post an STL for it. Any plastic disk about 4mm thick will do. Mounting to the smooth 8mm rod: You do not have to disassemble your printer, if you print PLA or similar material with flexibility, you should be able to snap it over the rod. I made the hole 8.5 mm to allow for this, but also allow it to secure well. Cleaning
Be sure to clean out the screw holes. They should pass the screws without needing to turn them, but not so much that they wobble or are loose. Sanding
The moving parts that touch each other should all be sanded smooth. The parts should slide smoothly but not wobble loosely.

Hardware
  • The adjustable thumb screw is an M5 with nut.
  • The nut holder must be cleaned up after printing as it is very snug (on purpose)
  • The "stop switch bracket" uses M3 nuts and bolts as does the rod mount.
  • Taking the time to smooth any printing ridges out, makes it move and work real nice.
  • Inside you can add a spring so when you loosen the thumb screw, it lowers without having to push it down. You would insert the sprint inside the "main mounting bracket" prior to inserting the "stop switch bracket."
  • I made the mount for the rod twice as tall as the typical zstop to give it more gripping power as not to slide or move once you have it set.

title: Da Vinci 1.0 E3D V6 hot end and MK9 extruder mount

description.text:
parts to mount a mk9 extruder to a e3d v6 on a xyz da vinci 1.0 carriage. you will need an assortment of m3 socket head cap screws and 3 nuts to assembly this. Requires cutting the carriage to fit as it raises the stepper motor so the nozzle is in the correct location. printer_motor_mount_1 is the backing plate used to stiffen up the carriage after the cut
remove the stock carriage, bolt this in place and scribe the new motor hole and drill the 2 new lower motor holes. remove and cut the scribe marks for the new motor clearance hole user printer motor mount 4 and 5 for a left hand extruder and 2 and 3 for a right hand extruder You will need to unwrap the nylon loom and separate the photo optic board harness from the loom, I stored it in the unused space in the filament cartridge area and extended the temp sensor wiring so that it reaches. The fan is soldered directly to the 12v power leads on the mother board so it is always on per the e3dv6 manual. The hole for the temp sensor needs to be drilled out to approximately 1/16 for the factory da vinci temp sensor. this is tested on an original da vinci 1.0 running firmware 1.1F and a mk9 feeder such as this one https://www.amazon.com/CTYRZCH-Filament-Extruder-Dedicated-Extrusion/dp/B01MXVIPKW and it works great. The all metal right hand drive pictured is running on a da vinci 1.0A running a ramps control. The right hand drive version will not work with the stock firmware as it offsets the extruder and requires reversing the motor drive.

I'll add more random things later like different motor mounts.
currently everything is setup to take m3 and m4 screws. Needs metal tierods to link the left and right pods to the common front and rear servos, which are mounted inboard. The arms are marked Left and Right for a reason, which is to keep the pivot axis in line with the servo arm rotation axis. These models have been optimized to print without any support material for the two body decks. You will need: m3 bolts of various sizes (nuts optional, as I've sized the holes for self tapping). small ball bearings for the tilt pods (or substitute appropriate 3d printed bushings). tie rods or L stock for the tilt linkages. optional carbon fiber landing feet from a turnigy talon frame. servo mounting screws. patience, as these prints take a while. comments.text:
I wouldn't go full 90 degree tilt if I were you. The tilt characteristic is mostly designed for cutting down the front facing surface area. Different motor and prop combinations will yield a different maximum tilt, as the lift out of ground effect would be proportional to the cosine of the tilt of the rotors' rotational axes to the ground plane multiplied by the maximum thrust of a given rotor/motor pairing. If this number is not greater than or equal to the force produced by gravity acting on the mass of the quadrotor, your flight will subsequently enter a state known as "crashing."
As far as diving, I'm not the best test pilot considering I can barely fly a regular quadrotor, so I encourage you to try it before resorting to pessimism. My experience with tilting the rotors had an abrupt ending facilitated by the side of my house, with lesser roles played by gravity, and my lawn.
If you go full tilt, it'll definitely eat it though.

This set of files are a set of brackets (left, right, center) meant for mounting a license plate or other strong and thin plate to the wall as an angled shelf. These particular STL files are for a shelf set to a 27º slope. In the Onshape project you can adjust this angle as a variable, as well as the thickness of your plate and a few other parameters. Due to the length of the object I intend to hold with the shelf (a soldering station), I later added an variable to offset the start point of the license plate within the bracket outward from the wall, leaving room for a thick power cord to hang. I've attached two sets of 3 STL files, one set for a shelf that is thinner and closer to the wall, and one set for the thicker, extended brackets. The attached screenshots also relate to these two different versions of the shelf. I haven't yet printed the extended version of the shelf, so the photos are of the thinner version. I've also exported the project from Onshape in Solidworks, Rhino, and Parasolid formats and have attached them. Perhaps these will allow offline editing. title: Dial Indicator Holder For Printrbot Simple Metal

description.text: This Thing holds a pretty cheep dial indicator and helps me with bed leveling and span calibration. To know the accuracy and repeat-ability of your machine is well worth the time invested. The Dial indicator fits snugly and requires assistance in the form of the pry bar. The dial indicator I used is: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002YPHT76 for about $30 I have a test routine and spreadsheet that helps me determine my current tolerance and repeat-ability that checks 75 points. I will one day soon hopefully replace that with a digital indicator and automatic (dis)engage to monitor performance and inform me of possible issues. The screw that holds it is 1/4-20 X 1.75in Phillips head and works with the nuts well. I was able to print it and just thread it right on to the screw.

Notes: I do my calibration with a sheet of paper (0.08mm or 0.003in) and I get it low enough that I see the needle move when I insert or remove the piece of paper. the calculations are very easy after that. Remember that 0.100in is 2.54mm, and give yourself good documentation when writing gcode. With my printrbot, I removed the Z-probe and added a limit switch (which I glued the wheel from rotating on since it was causing a variance of 0.020in). My zero is repeatable within +/- 0.0005, which is at the limit of what my measuring capabilities are, although I would not recommend modifying your printer as heavily as I have done (unless you like to break it and spend 30+ hours calibrating it and writing your own gcode for various operations, like removing autobed leveling and 75 point check :-). The Dial indicator holder could be modified to work with a normal Z-probe by removing a small section of the taller hole so that it snaps over the sensor.

description.text:
In general aviation aircraft, the round instruments mounted in cockpit panels are generally one of two common sizes: 2-1/4" (57mm) and 3-1/8" (80mm). MS33638
This thing is an adapter plate that allows you to utilize a 2-1/4" instrument in an aircraft panel hole that was designed to fit a 3-1/8" instrument.
The design is made so that the surface of the adapter should be able to sit flush with the surrounding panel, however the actual 2-1/4" instrument will be slightly recessed behind the inner cutout of the adapter. Traditionally purchased adapters of this style would normally have an inner overhang so that the 2-1/4" instrument can sit closer to the adapter's face, but this would unfortunately be more difficult to print.
Notes: It's recommended that you print using ABS (not PLA), since the cockpit environment can get very hot and will affect the strength and shape of PLA.

Mount using MS35214-27, 6-32 Instrument mounting screws or equivalent.
You may need to use instrument mounting nuts (A8943-632-493), Tinnerman nuts, or 6-32 machine nuts if the screw fit is not secure enough.

I have designed several 3D printers over the years and I have found that while bearings do work they often create a lot more friction than bushing. So, here it is, 3D printed bushings for the CNC center assembly instead of bearings. I have printed one of these just to get an idea of how well it will slide on the conduit and I must say it slides much better than I thought it would. Anyway let me know what you think and remember this is just an idea and most definitely a work in progress. I have added the SolidWorks file in case anyone else would like to make changes to my design. Update: 1/20/2016 I noticed during extensive testing that there was a fair amount of friction caused by the weight of the tool head pulling on the the z-axis causing the entire assembly to tilt so I added some bottom support in hopes that this will correct that issue. Once it is tested I will update this things status. I have also upload some new files with these changes as well. Update: 1/20/2016 After adding more support for the z-axis sadly it did not correct this problem. Do to the weight of the tool head it causes the entire part to tilt forward and this in turn causes the bottom axis to have more pressure on it. Which means it will not work. Unless someone has an idea how to solve this issue I think this idea is dead in the water. Update: 3/7/2016 - I have ordered 15/16" bunting bushings. Once I get them in hand I will change this design to fit the new bushings and give it a try. 3/16/2016 - I now have the bushing in hand http://www.ebay.com/itm/381483978314?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT and they fit the bars perfectly. I thought I would need to bore these out. Not necessary. Perfect fit. I have posted the untested update to support the bushings. However, I have included the Solidworks part so anyone can make changes to it if needed. $16 dollars for the bushings and a little PLA compared to all of the bearings and screws/nuts and complexity of putting the original center together I think it will be a real winner. Once mine finishes the print I will post the test results. I really think this is going to work based on how smooth these bushing run on the bars. 3/16/2016 - My print finished but I made a mistake in where the nut goes. It was a little off. I have repaired it in the model and if my test print works I will re-post the finished model for testing shortly. 3/18/2016 - Print went fine and bushings fit perfectly and everything lines up correctly. I will post a picture of the completed assembly shortly as well as a video when I get a chance to fully test it out.

title: MakerBot 5th Gen Dial Indicator, Smart Extruder Snap-on

description.text:
This is an fixture for an dail Indicator for the MakerBot 5th Gen 3D printers (5th Gen and Z18) to aid assistance for leveling the buildplate. We found that the build in leveling in the Z18 is not accurate enough. By using this fixture, you can get the leveling very accurate.
This fixture can placed in the same spot as the Smart Extruder. Just exchange it. It has the same magnets as the Smart Extruder. We just salvaged some form an old Smart Extruder we had lying around the workshop. The size of the magnets that will fit is 9.5 mm in diameter and 6.35 mm height. The hole for the dail Indicator is 8 mm in diameter. For the Z18 just start the leveling routine in the menu and when the build platform is in place, just cancel the procedure. The build plate is in the right position then. Losen all the bolts beneath the build plate as you would do for normal leveling.
Move the extruder carriage to the back center position, about the same position the set screw is for the leveling.
Set your dail indicator to zero. This is your reference point.
Than move the extruder carriage to the front right position above the front setscrew. We prefer to move the carriage by pulling the belt and to by touching the extruder carriage. If you touch the extruder carriage you could tilt it and that would influence the measurement.
Now turn the setscrew until the indicator is at zero again. Try to avoid pushing the setscrew. Just turing keeps the platform stable.
Repeat for the front left position and your done after tightening the screws of the platform again.
The normal offset between an default calibration and calibration with this dial indicator is between 0,1 and 0,3 mm. After this procedure the difference between the point should be less than the layer height. This improves adhesion to the buildplate a lot, especially for larger prints. We tried to move the gantry with Simlify3D, but that does not allow us to move anything manually. All the commands except loading and unloading filament are disabled. Anyone who has some ideas on how to do this, please let me know in the comments below. An way to automate the movement is very welcome and can only improve the accuracy of the measurement.

This is just for leveling and we just stop the machine when it is ready to start the leveling. Then the dail indicator in on the right height to do its thing. Just set it to zero and move the carriage to one of the other spots, preferably right above the sets crews. We found measurements up to 0,4 mm difference in height when performing an software assisted leveling first. It will definitely improve the overall printing special with regards to the leveling.

title: Hotshoe Diffuser Clip for SLR Camera

description.text: I sometimes need an impromptu diffuser to use with the built-in flash of my SLR camera. This small clip is installed after the built-in flash has been deployed, and provides support for a standard business card to be inserted white side up. The flash is thus bounced from the ceiling and lessens the harshness of the flash, e.g. for portraits. Thanks to TheCase for the original Nikon hotshoe cover model, from which this is derived. I found that the Nikon version had to be scaled by 0.95 to fit the Olympus SLR (E500) hotshoe. May work on other brands of SLR, depending on the configuration of the built-in flash - let me know if it works on your Canon or Nikon!

Printed at 1 extra shell/setting, 0.2 infill on my Prusa Mendel.
I found that I had to use a print speed of no more than 5-15 mm/s to get the overhang to print properly. While the print is still warm, use a flat head screwdriver to make sure that the space between the clip itself is open all the way across and clear of strings of plastic. On my prints I also used a Dremel to sand down the underside of the lower part of the clip, which had some hanging plastic.

Other fan things I have seen on thingiverse would not fit on my steppers, they all hit something or other preventing installation.  
If you use this thing make sure your Fan is 15mm thick.  I used an M4 bolt to mount fan; I drilled out the hole a little smaller than bolt so it threaded into the plastic. Installation was plenty tight to keep fan at desired angel.

title: Clip Bracket for LCD Smart Contol display on Makerfarm i3v 10"

description.text:
After experimenting with making some clips that slide over the wood and stay put without bolts, I came up with this idea to replace the wooden LCD Panel enclosure on my Makerfarm i3v 10". You can use 4 - M3x16mm socket head screws to mount the faceplate to the brackets & optionally you can mount the brackets to the wood frame with 2 - M3x20mm socket head screws. It is a little tight getting M3x20mm bolts attached, but they do fit for me. It stays on there pretty good without the bolts, but I put them on to make sure they fit. I would suggest printing the test parts 1st to make sure it fits ok for you, especially that the holes on the faceplate line up with your LCD controller. The faceplate by itself took me 2.5 hours to print. The 2 brackets took me 2:08 to print. I printed these in PETG at 20% infill. I run the wire for my X-motor across the top, so I added wire clips to my version, but you can print yours without that. I also included a control knob, but most people already have one of these printed. For the face plate I used dimensions & knob cutout dimensions from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35438 For the Control Knob I used some info from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35438
//and Part http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6194 I used the file: https://github.com/DonKahones/MakerFarm-Prusa-i3v-12-Inch to get the hole pattern spacing to mount to the frame. Since that is the 12" i3v, this should also work for the 12" with the same LCD panel and might work for the 8" i3v.
